      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the principal balance seems to be playing hide and seek with your hard-earned money. It's like a sneaky goblin, always lurking in the shadows, ready to snatch a bit of your gold coin each month. When you make your monthly payments, a portion of that gold goes straight to the principal, but a larger chunk goes to the interest, which is like the goblin's tax on your gold stash. The interest is calculated based on the remaining balance of your loan, so the more you owe, the more goblins are partying and demanding their share. It's a bit like trying to fill a leaking bucket with a hole in it; the goblins keep finding new holes to exploit, making it seem like your gold is vanishing into thin air. But fear not, brave borrower, for with each payment, you're slowly chipping away at the goblin's hoard, inching closer to the day when the goblins will have to share their loot with you. Keep making those monthly payments, and soon you'll see the principal balance start to shrink, goblins be damned!",
      "source": "target",
